{#- #1844 (epic #1836, the #1839-reshaped pipeline tail slice). The plugs unplugged-parity table.
    Unlike the build-time catalog-auto-render pages (which read `we:src/_data/*`), this page fetches the
    verdicts from the FUI MaaS parity route AT RUNTIME (`${links.frontierUrl}/_maas/parity/`, #1890) —
    the cross-origin data path #1839 mandates. WE holds ONLY the type-only schema (#1888); the measured
    3-state verdict VALUES are a FUI-runtime fact (#1839/#1282 zero-impl) and never live in a WE data file.
    The `data-parity-origin` attribute hands the (dev vs prod) FUI origin to the runtime fetcher. -#}

<section class="intro">
  <h1>Plug parity — works unplugged</h1>
  <p>
    Every plug runs today as a standalone library whether or not its capability ever ships natively — but
    "runs as a library" is not the same as "needs no plug". This table is the honest, per-public-API
    answer: for each plug capability, does it still work with the plug
    <strong>unplugged</strong> (the runtime patches removed), and if not, exactly what platform hook is
    missing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="content-box" style="margin: 0 0 2rem;">
  <h2 style="margin-top: 0;">How to read the verdicts</h2>
  <p>The marking vocabulary is the 3-state bar ratified in the unplugged-parity decision (caniuse-shaped):</p>
  <ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0; padding-left: 1.25rem;">
    <li>
      <we-badge tone="success">works</we-badge>
      &mdash; proven unplugged by an automated test exercising the real capability.
    </li>
    <li>
      <we-badge tone="warning">works with caveat</we-badge>
      &mdash; reachable unplugged but the surface is partial; carries a <strong>mandatory note</strong>.
      A capability that is merely <em>not-yet-ported</em> (portable, no genuine residue) also lands here,
      with a link to the fix card that will move it to <em>works</em>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <we-badge tone="danger">plugged-only</we-badge>
      &mdash; genuine residue: the contract requires interception the plug holds no handle to. Carries a
      <strong>residue justification</strong> naming the missing platform hook.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0; color: var(--color-text-muted); font-size: 0.9em;">
    The verdicts are measured live by Frontier UI and fetched from its data origin when this page loads &mdash;
    Web Everything itself holds only the parity schema, never the values.
  </p>
</section>

<section style="margin: 1.5rem 0 1rem;">
  <div style="flex: 1; min-width: 220px; max-width: 420px;">
    <h3 style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem; font-size: 0.85em; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; color: var(--color-text-muted);">Search</h3>
    <input type="search" id="parity-search" placeholder="Filter by plug, capability, note, or residue…"
           style="width: 100%; padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem; border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: 6px; font-size: 0.9em; background: var(--color-surface, #fff);">
  </div>
</section>

<div id="parity-root" data-parity-origin="{{ links.frontierUrl }}">
  <p id="parity-loading" style="color: var(--color-text-muted); margin: 1.5rem 0;">Loading parity verdicts…</p>
  <p id="parity-error" hidden style="margin: 1.5rem 0;"></p>
  <div id="parity-domains"></div>
  <p id="parity-empty" hidden style="text-align: center; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin: 2rem 0;">No capabilities match.</p>
</div>

